Task 1.1 - The Problem

For this assessment, I will attempt to create an image classifier which can tell if an item is rubbish or recycling as per my council area (Hornsby Council NSW).

In the ultimate app, I would like users to know not only if something should be in the rubbish or recycling bin, but if they can take their object somewhere else to be recycled e.g. if it's electronic waste, where can they take that? Where should I take used motor oil or old batteries?

The classifier I create for this assessment will start with a basic binary classifier, either rubbish or recycling, and will improve to a multiclass classifier in the future as more data is collected through the app.

Hornsby Council recycling bins can take items such as glass jars, milk cartons, steel cans, pizza boxes and some plastics. For simplicity, my image classifier will begin by including cardboard, cans and glass bottles in it's recycling set.

Items that Hornsby Council cannot take in the recylcing bin are those such as soft plastics, coffee cups, nappies, shredded paper and green waste. My rubbish dataset will start off with food scraps, plastic bags and plastic straws.

As the app is used more and more by those in the community, it will collect labelled data to improve functionality.

https://www.hornsby.nsw.gov.au/property/waste/your-weekly-collection/what-can-i-put-in-my-bins

Task 1.2 - The Plan

To start with, I found an organic and reyclable dataset on Kaggle. After downloading this set and looking through the images, I found that both the images in the organic set and the recycling set were not in line with what is allowable in the Hornsby coucnil. As I was not able to find a dataset that contained what I needed, I decided to manually sort through the Kaggle set myself.

After several iterations of different training and test data, I decided to create a binary classifier with only a few different forms of rubbish and recycling to get the classifier started. I had attempted a multiclass classifier but with poor performance and so I settled on binary. When creating the binary classifier, I discovered that if I did not include enough recycling or rubbish items of a similar type then the classifier performed poorly. Thus, I decided to create the dataset with many images in each sublcass of rubbish and recycling, and decided to get the classifier started by using only a few sub-types of each category to begin with.

From the kaggle images, I created a dataset including the following:

Training:

  • Recycling
    • 50 images of cardboard
    • 50 images of glass bottles
    • 50 images of cans
  • Rubbish
    • 50 images of plastic bags
    • 50 images of plastic straws
    • 50 images of organic waste

Validation:

  • Recycling
    • 25 images of cardboard
    • 25 images of glass bottles
    • 25 images of cans
  • Rubbish
    • 25 images of plastic bags
    • 25 images of plastic straws
    • 25 images of organic waste

Test:

  • Recycling
    • 5 images of cardboard
    • 5 images of glass bottles
    • 5 images of cans
  • Rubbish
    • 5 images of plastic bags
    • 5 images of plastic straws
    • 5 images of organic waste

I created folders for training, test, and validate with sub-folders of recycling and rubbish so that labelled images could be imported using the Keras ImageDataGenerator package. I also created a folder titled 'my_rubish' which contains 7 images of my own rubbish that I have taken with my own phone. A folder titled 'my_model' creates my saved final model. Data can be accessed via this link https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/16AbI5ZtoyXoTg6Sa5oHAP-gpc811Ync1

I decided on a baseline for success of my model would be if it beats an accuracy of 0.5. As I will be creating a binary classifier with balanced samples for each class, anything >0.5 indicates that the classifer performs better than chance. I feel that anything >0.5 would indicate my model has potential, a high level of accuracy would be needed before public release of a rubbish/recycling classifier app. As contaminated recycling can cause an entire load of recycling to be thrown away, it would be important that the algorithm is very unlikely to misclassify rubbish as recycling before public release. If the algorithm never misclassified rubbish as recycling then it would be a success, however it would be acceptable if the algorithm sometimes misclassified recycling as rubbish.

For this algorithm, I have accepted that within my time and resource contraints, I will not be able to collect enough real-world data, of rubbish that individuals might take themselves with phone camears in poor lighting with many different backgrounds. I simply hope that the algorithm can provide a base to be improved upon as users upload much data.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/techsash/waste-classification-data

# Create a sequential model with three convolutional layers

model = tf.keras.models.Sequential([tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(16,(3,3),activation='relu', input_shape=(200,200,3)),
                                    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32,(3,3),activation='relu'),
                                    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64,(3,3),activation='relu'),
                                    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='relu'),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1,activation='sigmoid')
                                    
                                    ])

How does my model perform?

The plots show that although the training loss has decreased and accuracy increased, as is desirable, validation accuracy has had marginal if any improvement in accuracy after just 2 epochs, and has had increasing loss scores.

The results indicate that the model is overfitting. I initially tried decreasing the learning rate, however this returned poor results and I returned to the initial learning rate of 0.001. I also tried several different batch sizes, with most succesful batch sizes being smaller ones.

The model may be corrected using data augmentation, such as in the next step. Alternatively, more data may be required to improve the model performance.

In [87]:
start2 = time.time()

aug_model = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
                                    data_augmentation,
                                    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(16,(3,3),activation='relu', input_shape=(200,200,3)),
                                    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32,(3,3),activation='relu'),
                                    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64,(3,3),activation='relu'),
                                    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='relu'),

                                    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1,activation='sigmoid')
                                    
                                    ])

aug_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
              optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=0.001),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

aug_history = aug_model.fit(train,
                      epochs=30,
                      batch_size=32,
                      validation_data=validation)

end2=time.time()
print("Run time is [s]", end2-start2)

Augmenting the data considerably improved the model, with much less overfitting compared to the first model. Accuracy was somewhat improved on the validation data compared to the original model and loss score was reduced. The model took considerably longer to train compared to the model without image augmentation, as was expected. However, considering the reduction in overfitting this is certainly worthwhile.

Overfitting could be further reduced by adding more data. Now that the model runs effectively this is something I would be comfortable implementing.

When model performance was viewed on the seperate test set it performed reasonably well, although there were some mistakes. It did seem that images with some extraneous information were not classified as well, such as the beer pottles that included a bottle opener and the can of coke that includes an image of a tooth! Furtermore, pizza boxes with images on top were more likely to be misclassified. This is expected and indicates that either more data is needed and/or the model could benefit by removing these kinds of images from the training set.
